The '''Adriatic Sea''' ({{IPAc-en|icon|<U+02CC>|e<U+026A>|d|r|i|<U+02C8>|<U+00E6>|t|<U+0268>|k}}) is a body of water separating the [[Apennine Peninsula]] from the [[Balkan peninsula]], and the [[Apennine Mountains]] from that of the [[Dinaric Alps]] and adjacent ranges.  The Adriatic Sea is the northernmost arm of the [[Mediterranean Sea]] extending from the [[Strait of Otranto]], where it connects to the [[Ionian Sea]], to the Northwest and the [[Po Valley]]. Its coasts belong to [[Italy]], [[Slovenia]], [[Croatia]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Montenegro]] and [[Albania]]. The Adriatic contains more than a [[List of islands in the Adriatic|thousand islands]], largely located along its Eastern coast. The Adriatic is divided into three basins&mdash;the Northern being the shallowest and the Southern being the deepest, where the maximum depth of {{convert|1233|m|abbr=off}} is recorded. Otranto Sill is located at the border of the Adriatic and Ionian seas. Prevailing currents flow in counterclockwise direction from the Strait of Otranto, along the Eastern coast and back to the strait along the Western, Italian coast. Tidal movement is slight, although [[acqua alta|larger amplitudes]] are known to occur occasionally. Salinity of the Adriatic is lower compared to the Mediterranean as the former collects a third of freshwater flowing into the latter, acting as a [[dilution basin]]. Surface water temperature generally ranges from {{convert|24|C|F}} in summer to {{convert|12|C|F}} in winter, significantly moderating climate of the Adriatic basin. Shores of the Adriatic are populated by more than 3.5&nbsp;million people, and the largest cities are [[Bari]], [[Venice]], [[Trieste]] and [[Split, Croatia|Split]].

The Adriatic Sea sits on [[Apulian Plate|Apulian or Adriatic Microplate]] which separated from the [[African Plate]] in [[Mesozoic]]. Movement of the plate contributed to [[Alpine orogeny]] and uplift of the Apennines. All types of sediment are found in the Adriatic, with bulk of the material transported by the [[Po (river)|Po]] and other rivers on the West coast. The Western coast is [[Flat coast|alluvial]] or [[Marine terrace|terraced]], while the Eastern coast is well indented with pronounced [[karst|karstification]]. There are 15 [[marine protected area]]s in the Adriatic designed to protect the karst [[habitat]]s and [[biodiversity]] of the sea. The sea is abundant in flora and fauna&mdash;more than 7,000 species are identified as native to the Adriatic, including [[Endemism|endemic]], rare and threatened ones.

The earliest settlements on the Adriatic shores were [[Etruscan civilization|Etruscan]], [[Illyria]]n, and [[Classical Greece|Greek]]. By the 2nd century BC, the shores were under full control of the [[Roman Republic|Rome]]. In the [[Middle Ages]], the Adriatic shores and the sea itself was controlled, to a varying extent, by a series of states&mdash;most notably the [[Byzantine Empire]], the [[Republic of Venice]], the [[Habsburg Monarchy]] and the [[Ottoman Empire]]. The [[Napoleonic Wars]] resulted in [[First French Empire|French]] control of the coasts and [[Adriatic campaign of 1807<U+2013>1814|British effort]] to counter the French in the area, ultimately securing most of the Eastern Adriatic and the Po Valley for [[Austrian Empire|Austria]]. Following [[Italian unification|unification]], [[Kingdom of Italy (1861<U+2013>1946)|Italy]] started eastward expansion which would last until the 20th century. Following the [[World War I]] and collapse of [[Austria-Hungary]] and the Ottoman Empire, control of the Eastern coast passed to [[Yugoslavia]] and Albania. The former [[breakup of Yugoslavia|disintegrated]] in 1990s, resulting in four new states on the Adriatic shores. 

The Adriatic Sea is significant for economies of the countries found along its coasts, especially in terms of [[Fishery|fisheries]] and tourism. The [[NUTS of Croatia|Adriatic Croatia]] recently records comparably greater growth relative to the rest of the Adriatic basin. Maritime transport is also a significant branch of economy in the area&mdash;there are 19 major seaports in the Adriatic handling more than a million tonnes of cargo per year. The largest Adriatic seaport by annual cargo turnover is the [[Port of Trieste]], while the [[Port of Split]] is the largest Adriatic seaport in terms of number of passengers served per year. Italy and former Yugoslavia defined their maritime boundaries by 1975 and the boundary is recognized by Yugoslavia's successor states, but maritime boundaries between Slovene, Croatian, Bosnia and Herzegovinian and Montenegrin waters are disputed. Italy and Albania defined their maritime boundary in 1992.

==Geography==
[[File:Zatoka Kotorska.jpg|thumb|right|[[Bay of Kotor]], a [[ria]] in the Southern Adriatic]]
Adriatic Sea is bordered by the [[Apennine peninsula]] in the southwest, [[Italy|Italian]] regions of [[Veneto]] and [[Friuli-Venezia Giulia]] in the northwest, and in the northeast by [[Slovenia]], [[Croatia]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Montenegro]] and [[Albania]]&mdash;the [[Balkan peninsula]]. In the southeast, the Adriatic Sea connects to the [[Ionian Sea]] at the {{convert|72|km|adj=on}} wide [[Strait of Otranto]].<ref name="CRGP-p1-2">Cushman-Roisin, Ga<U+010D>i<U+0107>, Poulain; pp. 1&ndash;2</ref> The [[International Hydrographic Organization]] (IHO) defines the boundary between the Adriatic and the Ionian seas as a line running from the mouth of the [[Butrint|Butrinto River]] (39<U+00B0>44'N) in Albania to Cape Karagol in [[Corfu]], through this island to Cape Kephali (these two capes are in lat. 39<U+00B0>45'N) and on to [[Santa Maria di Leuca|Cape Santa Maria di Leuca]].<ref name="IHO-boundary">{{cite web|url=http://www.iho-ohi.net/iho_pubs/standard/S-23/S23_1953.pdf|title=Limits of Oceans and Seas, 3rd edition|year=1953|publisher=International Hydrographic Organization|accessdate=7 February 2010}}</ref> It extends {{convert|800|km|abbr=off}} from the northwest to the southeast and it is {{convert|200|km|abbr=off}} wide. It covers {{convert|138600|km2|abbr=off}} and comprises volume of {{convert|35000|km3|abbr=off}}. The Adriatic extends northwest from [[40th parallel north|40<U+00B0>]] to 45<U+00B0>47' North, representing the northernmost portion of the [[Mediterranean]].<ref name="CRGP-p1-2"/> Adriatic Sea [[drainage basin]] encompasses {{convert|235000|km2|abbr=off}}, yielding land to sea ratio of 1.8. Mean elevation of the drainage basin is {{convert|782|m|abbr=off}} above sea level, while its mean slope is 12.1<U+00B0>.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=SESAME|url=http://www.sesame-ip.eu/doc/prooce_wl_inpress.pdf|format=PDF|title=River discharges of water and nutrients to the Mediterranean and Black Sea: Major drivers for ecosystem changes during past and future decades?|authors=Wolfgang Ludwig et al.|year=2009|accessdate=27 January 2012}}</ref> Major rivers discharging into the Adriatic are Po, [[So<U+010D>a]], [[Krka (Croatia)|Krka]], [[Neretva]], [[Drin (river)|Drin]], [[Bojana (river)|Bojana]] and [[Vjos<U+00EB>]] rivers.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[United Nations Economic Commission for Europe]]|url=http://www.unece.org/fileadmin/DAM/env/water/publications/assessment/English/J_PartIV_Chapter6_En.pdf|format=PDF|title=Drainage Basin of the Mediterranean Sea|accessdate=27 January 2012}}</ref>

