The Adriatic Sea contains well more than a thousand [[List of islands in the Adriatic|islands and islets]]. By far, the most of them are located along the Eastern coast of the Adriatic, especially in Croatia where 1,246 are found. The number includes [[islands]], [[islets]], and rocks of all sizes, including ones emerging at ebb tide only.<ref>{{cite journal|publisher=[[University of Zadar]]|url=http://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=84063|author1=Josip Fari<U+010D>i<U+0107>|author2=Vera Graovac|author3=Anica <U+010C>uka||pages=145-185|title=Croatian small islands <U+2013> residential and/or leisure area|journal=Geoadria|volume=15|issue=1|year=2010|month=June|accessdate=28 January 2012}}</ref> The Croatian islands include the largest&mdash;[[Cres]] and [[Krk]] each covering {{convert|405.78|km2|abbr=off}}, and the tallest&mdash;[[Bra<U+010D>]] whose peak reaches {{convert|780|m|abbr=off}} above sea level. The Croatian islands include 48 [[List of inhabited islands of Croatia|permanently inhabited ones]], the most populous among them being Krk and [[Kor<U+010D>ula]].<ref>{{cite journal|publisher=[[Croatian Bureau of Statistics]]|format=PDF|url=http://www.dzs.hr/Hrv_Eng/ljetopis/2011/SLJH2011.pdf|journal=2011 Statistical Yearbook of the Republic of Croatia|issn=1333-3305|month=December|year=2011|volume=43|title=Geographical and Meteorological Data|page=41|accessdate=28 January 2012}}</ref> Islands found along the Western coast of the Adriatic Sea are smaller and less numerous in comparison to those along the opposite coast. The best known Adriatic islands found along the Western, i.e. Italian coast are 117 islands on which the city of [[Venice]] is built.<ref>{{cite book|page=481|title=Mediterranean Europe|author=Duncan Garwood|publisher=[[Lonely Planet]]|year=2009|isbn=9781741048568|accessdate=29 January 2012}}</ref> Northern shore of [[Greece|Greek]] island of [[Corfu]] also lies in the Adriatic sea, as defined by the IHO.<ref>{{cite book|page=58|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=ajhU1AAacUsC|title=Frommer's 500 Extraordinary Islands|authors=Holly Hughes, Alexis Lipsitz Flippin, Sylvie Murphy, Julie Duchaine|publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]]|isbn=9780470500705|year=2010|accessdate=29 January 2012}}</ref> The IHO boundary also places few smaller Greek islands northwest of Corfu in the Adriatic Sea.<ref name="IHO-boundary"/><ref>{{Google maps | url = http://maps.google.com/maps?q=cape+kephali,+greece&hl=en&ie=UTF8&ll=39.838068,19.25354&spn=1.090324,2.705383&sll=39.712469,19.647675&sspn=0.273083,0.676346&oq=Cape+&hnear=%C3%81kra+Kavokefal%C3%AD&t=m&z=9 | title = Cape Kephali, Corfu, Greece - the southernmost point of the Adriatic Sea | accessdate = 29 January 2012}}</ref>
{{wide image|Adriatic_Sea_islands.jpg|1000px|<center>Adriatic Sea ([[Croatia]])</center>}}

===Bathymetry===
North Adriatic basin, extending between Venice and [[Trieste]] towards a line connecting [[Ancona]] and [[Zadar]], is only {{convert|15|m|abbr=off}} deep at its northwestern end, and it gradually deepens towards the southeast. Middle Adriatic basin extends south of the Ancona&ndash;Zadar line, as {{convert|270|m|adj=on}} deep Middle Adriatic Pit (also called Pomo Depression or Jabuka Pit).
{{convert|170|m|adj=on}} deep Palagru<U+017E>a Sill is south of the Middle Adriatic Pit, separating it from {{convert|1200|m|adj=on}} deep South Adriatic Pit and the Middle Adriatic basin from the South Adriatic Basin. Further on to the south, the sea floor rises to {{convert|780|m|abbr=off}} to form Otranto Sill at the boundary to the Ionian Sea. Transversally, the Adriatic Sea is also asymmetric as the [[Apennine peninsula]] coast is relatively smooth with very few islands and [[promontory]] of [[Monte Conero]] and [[Gargano Promontory]] as only significant protrusions into the sea. On the other hand, the Balkan peninsula coast is rugged with numerous islands, especially in Croatia. Ruggedness of the coast is exacerbated by proximity of the [[Dinaric Alps]] to the coast, in contrast to the opposite, Italian coast, where the [[Apennine Mountains]] are further away from the shoreline.<ref name="CRGP-p2-6">Cushman-Roisin, Ga<U+010D>i<U+0107>, Poulain; pp. 2&ndash;6</ref> Average depth of the Adriatic sea is {{convert|252|m|abbr=off}}, while its maximum depth is {{convert|1233|m|abbr=off}}. Still, the North Adriatic basin rarely exceeds depth of {{convert|100|m|abbr=off}}.<ref name="BTS-Adriatic"/>

===Hydrology===
[[File:Adriatic jadran.png|thumb|left|Currents and salinity on cross-sections of the East (A) and the West (B) Adriatic]]
Dynamics of coastal waters are determined by the asymmetric coasts and inflow of Mediterranean seawater through the Straits of Otranto and further on along the Eastern coast.<ref name="Adriamed"/> The smooth Italian coast, comprising very few protrusions into the sea and no major islands allows smooth flow of the Western Adriatic Current, while coastal currents on the opposite shore are far more complex because of jagged appearance of the shoreline, several large islands and proximity of the Dinaric Alps to the shore. The latter produces significant temperature variations between the sea and hinterland, which is conductive surrounding to creation of local jets.<ref name="CRGP-p2-6"/> Tidal movement is slight, normally remaining below {{convert|30|cm|abbr=off}}. The [[amphidromic point]] is at mid-width east of Ancona.<ref name="CRGP-p218">Cushman-Roisin, Ga<U+010D>i<U+0107>, Poulain; p. 218</ref>

The normal tide levels are known to increase abnormally in conductive environment, leading to coastal flooding, most famously known in Italy, especially Venice, as [[acqua alta]]. They can exceed normal tide levels by more than {{convert|140|cm|abbr=off}}, with the highest tide level of {{convert|194|cm|abbr=off}} observed on 4 November 1966. Such flooding is caused by a combination of factors, including alignment of the [[Sun]] and the [[Moon]], geometric shape of the basin, which amplifies or reduces the astronomical component and meteorological factors such as atmospheric pressure and winds. Also, the long and narrow rectangular shape of the Adriatic Sea is the source of an oscillating water motion&mdash;[[seiche]] along the basin's minor axis<ref>Introduction to ''Previsioni di Marea nell'Alto Adriatico'' (in Italian), Venice, issue 29 of year 29, by Stefano Fracon</ref> Finally, Venice is increasingly vulnerable to flooding because of [[subsidence]] of coastal area soil.<ref name="Centro_Maree">{{cite web|url=http://www.comune.venezia.it/flex/cm/pages/ServeBLOB.php/L/IT/IDPagina/3045|language=Italian|title=Venice Municipality - Tide Monitoring and Forecast Center - Weather and sea parameters and their statistics}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[BBC News]]|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/8428781.stm|title=Flood waters drench city of Venice|date=23 December 2009|accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref> Such floods were also observed elsewhere in the Adriatic Sea, and have been recorded in recent years in [[Koper]], Zadar and [[<U+0160>ibenik]] as well.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Nova TV (Croatia)]]|language=Croatian|url=http://dnevnik.hr/vijesti/svijet/u-zasnijezenoj-sloveniji-raste-vodostaj-rijeka-more-poplavilo-obalu.html|title=U Sloveniji more poplavilo obalu|trans_title=Sea floods shore in Slovenia|date=9 November 2010|accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Nova TV (Croatia)]]|language=Croatian|title=Zadar: Zbog velike plime more poplavilo obalu|trans_title=Zadar: Sea floods shore because of high tide|url=http://dnevnik.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/zadar-zbog-plime-more-poplavilo-rivu.html|date=25 December 2009|accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|publisher=index.hr|language=Croatian|url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/jugo-i-niski-tlak-more-poplavilo-sibensku-rivu/526311.aspx|title=Jugo i niski tlak: More poplavilo <U+0161>ibensku rivu|Sirocco and low pressure: Sea floods <U+0160>ibenik quay|date=1 December 2010|accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref>

[[File:Vrulja kod Omi<U+0161>a.jpg|thumb|right|A submarine spring near [[Omi<U+0161>]], observed through rippling of the sea surface]]
It is estimated that the entire volume of the Adriatic Sea is exchanged through the Strait of Otranto in 3.4<U+00B1>0.4&nbsp;years, which is a comparably short period. For instance, approximatey 500&nbsp;years are necessary to exchange all water of the [[Black Sea]]. This is particularly important as rivers flowing into the Adriatic [[Discharge (hydrology)|discharge]] up to {{convert|5700|m3/s|abbr=off}}. That rate of discharge amounts to 0.5% of total Adriatic Sea volume or a {{convert|1.3|m|adj=on}} layer of water each year. The greatest portion of the discharge from any single river comes from the [[Po (river)|Po]] (28%),<ref>{{cite journal|publisher=Institute for Medical Research and Occupational Health|issn=0004-1254|journal=Archives of Industrial Hygiene and Toxicology|title=Marine Radioecology and Waste Management in the Adriatic|url=http://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=7507&lang=en|author1=Zdenko Frani<U+0107>|author2=Branko Petrinec|volume=57|issue=3|year=2006|month=September|pages=347-352|accessdate=04 February 2012}}</ref> whose average discharge alone is {{convert|1569|m3/s|abbr=off}}.<ref>{{cite book|page=6|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=UFHNGHADv5IC|title=The Mediterranean Sea|author=Alain Saliot|isbn=9783540250180|year=2005|publisher=Birkh<U+00E4>user|accessdate=27 January 2012}}</ref> In terms of annual discharge in the Mediterranean Sea, Po is ranked the second, followed by Neretva and Drin which are rank as the third and the fourth.<ref>{{cite book|chapter=1.6 Hydrology and Biogeochemistry|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=GDmX5XKkQCcC|title=Rivers of Europe|authors=Klement Tockner, Urs Uehlinger, Christopher T. Robinson|publisher=Academic Press|year=2009|isbn=9780123694492|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref> Another significant contributor of freshwater to the Adriatic is [[submarine groundwater discharge]] (SGD) through submarine springs ({{lang-hr|vrulja}}). The SGD is estimated to comprise 29% of total water flux in the Adriatic.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.clas.ufl.edu/users/jbmartin/website/Classes/Surface_Groundwater/Class%206/Taniguchi%20et%20al.%202002%20Hydrological%20processes%20review.pdf|format=PDF|title=Investigation of submarine groundwater discharge|authors=Makoto Taniguchi et al.|journal=Hydrological Processes|issn=1099-1085|publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]]|year=2002|pages=2115-2159|volume=16|accessdate=27 January 2012}}</ref> The submarine springs also include [[thermal springs]], discovered off shore near the town of [[Izola]]. The thermal water is rich with [[hydrogen sulfide]], has the temperature of {{convert|22|to|29.6|C|F}}, and has enabled the development of specific ecosystems.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Geografski Obzornik|year=2004|volume=51|issue=2|issn=0016-7274|publisher=Association of the Geographical Societies of Slovenia|language=Slovene|author=Jo<U+017E>e <U+017D>umer|title=Odkritje podmorskih termalnih izvirov|trans_title=Discovery of submarine thermal springs|pages=11-17|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref> The inflow of freshwater, representing one third of freshwater volume flowing into the Mediterranean,<ref>{{cite book|page=380|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=vY650GD-OLkC|title=Marine eutrophication and population dynamics|author=Giuseppe Colombo|publisher=Olsen & Olsen|year=1992|isbn=9788785215192|accessdate=28 January 2012}}</ref> gives the Adriatic characteristics of a [[dilution basin]] of the Mediterranean Sea.<ref name="CRGP-p145">Cushman-Roisin, Ga<U+010D>i<U+0107>, Poulain; p. 145</ref>

===Temperature and salinity===
Surface temperature of the Adriatic sea largely ranges from {{convert|22|to|24|C|F}} in summer, or {{convert|12|to|14|C|F}} in winter, except along the northern part of the western Adriatic coast, where the surface temperature drop to {{convert|9|C|F}}. The seasonal temperature variations are attributed to heat flux exchanged with the atmosphere. [[Salinity]] of the Adriatic sea ranges between 38 and 39&nbsp;[[Practical salinity unit|PSUs]].<ref name="Artegiani">{{cite journal|journal=[[Journal of Physical Oceanography]]|issn=0022-3670|publisher=[[American Meteorological Society]]|url=http://journals.ametsoc.org/doi/pdf/10.1175/1520-0485(1997)027%3C1492%3ATASGCP%3E2.0.CO%3B2|format=PDF|title=The Adriatic Sea General Circulation. Part I: Air<U+2013>Sea Interactions and Water Mass Structure|volume=27|month=August|year=1997|authors=Artegiani et al.|pages=1492-1514|accessdate=27 January 2012}}</ref> In shallow coastal areas of the Adriatic [[sea ice]] may appear in particularly cold winters&mdash;especially in the [[Venetian Lagoon]],<ref>{{cite book|pages=47-53|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=JD8CqjuA4SAC|title=Mediterranean climate variability|authors=Piero Lionello, Paola Malanotte-Rizzoli, R. Boscolo|publisher=Elsevier|year=2006|isbn=9780444521705|accessdate=2 February 2012}}</ref> but also in isolated shallow areas as far south as [[Tisno]] south of Zadar.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[RTL Televizija]]|url=http://www.rtl.hr/vijesti/novosti/24169/led-okovao-svjetionik-u-tisnom-smrznulo-more/|language=Croatian|title=Led okovao svjetionik, u Tisnom smrznulo more|trans_title=Ice covers a lighthouse, sea freezes at Tisno|date=16 December 2010|accessdate=2 February 2012}}</ref>

===Climate===
As in most of the areas in the [[Mediterranean Basin]], the Adriatic Sea and its surrounding landmass enjoy [[Mediterranean climate]], a particular variety of [[subtropical climate]]. Since the Adriatic Sea is located at [[mid-latitudes]], it is characterized by seasonal variability of climate. The climate is characterized by warm to hot, dry summers and mild to cool, wet winters. Air temperature fluctuates by about {{convert|20|C|F}} during a season.<ref name="Artegiani"/> According to the [[K<U+00F6>ppen climate classification]], the southern and central Adriatic are classified as hot-summer Mediterranean climate (Csa), and the northern Adriatic as [[Humid subtropical climate]] (Cfa) climate areas.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Salento]]|format=PDF|url=http://www.dsm.unisalento.it/webutenti/piero.lionello/public/book/mb_0_PL/chapter0_V6.pdf|title=Mediterranean climate: Background information|accessdate=27 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|publisher=[[University of Zadar]]|url=http://hrcak.srce.hr/9626|author1=Tomislav <U+0160>egota|author2=Anita Filip<U+010D>i<U+0107>|language=Croatian|pages=17-37|title=K<U+00F6>ppenova podjela klima i hrvatsko nazivlje|trans_title=K<U+00F6>ppen climate classification and Croatian terminology|journal=Geoadria|volume=8|issue=1|year=2003|month=June|accessdate=27 January 2012}}</ref> Predominant winter winds are [[Bora (wind)|bora]] and [[sirocco]] (''jugo''). Bora is significantly conditioned by wind gaps in the Dinaric Alps bringing cold and dry continental air, and it reaches peak speed in areas of Trieste, [[Senj]], and [[Split, Croatia|Split]], with gusts of up to {{convert|180|km/h|kn mph|-1|abbr=on}}. Sirocco, conversely, brings humid and warm air often carrying [[Sahara]]n sand and causing [[rain dust]].<ref name="CRGP-p6-8">Cushman-Roisin, Ga<U+010D>i<U+0107>, Poulain; pp. 6&ndash;8</ref>

