On the coasts and islands of the Adriatic Sea there are numerous settlements, but there are few larger cities. Among the largest there are [[Bari]], [[Venice]], [[Trieste]], [[Ravenna]] and [[Rimini]] in Italy, [[Split, Croatia|Split]], [[Rijeka]] and [[Zadar]] in Croatia, [[Durr<U+00EB>s]] and [[Vlor<U+00EB>]] in Albania and [[Koper]] in Slovenia. In total, more than 3.5&nbsp;million people live at the Adriatic coasts.<ref>{{cite journal|publisher=Croatian Geographic Society|issn=1331-5854|journal=Hrvatski geografski glasnik|author1=Bogdan Sekuli<U+0107>|author2=Ivan Sondi|volume=59|issue=1|month=December|year=1997|url=http://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=95871|accessdate=27 January 2012|title=Koliko je Jadran doista optere<U+0107>en antropogenim i prirodnim unosom tvari?|language=Croatian|trans_title=To What Extent is the Adriatic Sea Actually Burdened with Men-induced and Natural Inflow of Substances}}</ref>

==Coastal management==
[[File:MOSE Project Venice from the air.jpg|thumb|right|MOSE Project north of [[Lido di Venezia]]]]
[[Venice]], which was originally built on islands off the coast, is most at risk due to [[subsidence]], but the effect is realized in the Po delta as well. The causes are a decrease in the sedimentation rate due to loss of sediment behind dams and the deliberate excavation of sand for industrial purposes agricultural use of water, and removal of ground water.<ref name=WW>{{cite web|title=Facing Water Challenges in the Po River Basin, Italy:A WWDR3 Case Study|url=http://waterwiki.net/index.php/Facing_Water_Challenges_in_the_Po_River_Basin,_Italy:A_WWDR3_Case_Study|publisher=waterwiki.net|year=2009|accessdate=6 April 2009}}</ref><ref name=AM>{{cite web|title=Po Basin Case study status report|first=Meri|last=Raggi|coauthors=Davide Ronchi; Laura Sardonini;  Davide Viaggi|publisher=AquaMoney|year=2007|format=pdf|accessdate=6 April 2009|url=http://www.aquamoney.ecologic-events.de/sites/download/poit.pdf}}</ref>

Sinking of the city slowed since use of the artesian wells was banned in the 1960s, but the city remains threatened by the acqua alta floods. Recent studies suggested that the city is no longer sinking,<ref>{{cite journal |coauthors = |title = Technology: Venetians put barrage to the test against the Adriatic |issue = 1660 |publisher=[[New Scientist]] magazine |date = 15 April 1989 |url = http://media.newscientist.com/article/mg12216602.900-technology-venetians-put-barrage-to-the-test-against-theadriatic-.html |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071011072114/http://media.newscientist.com/article/mg12216602.900-technology-venetians-put-barrage-to-the-test-against-theadriatic-.html |archivedate = 11 October 2007 |id = |accessdate =10 October 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title = Venice's 1,500-year battle with the waves |publisher=BBC News  |date = 17 July 2003 |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/3069305.stm |accessdate =10 October 2007}}</ref> but a state of alert remains in place. In May 2003 the Italian Prime Minister [[Silvio Berlusconi]] inaugurated the [[MOSE project]] ({{lang-it|Modulo Sperimentale Elettromeccanico}}), an experimental model for evaluating the performance of inflatable gates. The project proposes laying a series of 79 inflatable [[pontoon (boat)|pontoons]] across the sea bed at the three entrances to the Venetian Lagoon. When tides are predicted to rise above {{convert|110|cm|abbr=off}}, the pontoons will be filled with air and block the incoming water from the Adriatic Sea. This engineering work is due to be completed by 2014.<ref>{{cite news |title = 'Moses project' to secure future of Venice |publisher= Telegraph News |date = 11 January 2012 |url =  http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/italy/3629387/Moses-project-to-secure-future-of-Venice.html|accessdate =11 January 2012}}</ref>

==Geology==
[[File:Adriatic Plate.jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Apulian Plate|Adriatic Microplate]] boundaries]]
Geophysical and geological information indicate that the the Adriatic Sea and the [[Po Valley]] are are associated with a [[List of tectonic plates|microplate]] which separated from the [[African Plate]]&mdash;identified as [[Apulian Plate|Apulian or Adriatic Plate]] during the [[Mesozoic]] era. The separation began in [[Middle Triassic|Middle]] and [[Late Triassic]], when [[limestone]] begins sedimenting in the area. Between [[Norian]] and [[Late Cretaceous]], [[Adriatic Carbonate Platform|Adriatic]] and [[Apulia Carbonate Platform]]s form as thick series of carbonate sediments ([[dolomite]]s and limestones), up to {{convert|8000|m|abbr=off}} deep.<ref name="Suri<U+0107>">{{cite journal|publisher=[[University of Zadar]]|issn=1331-2294|url=http://hrcak.srce.hr/9653|journal=Geoadria|title=Submerged Karst <U+2013> Dead or Alive? Examples from the Eastern Adriatic Coast (Croatia)|author=Ma<U+0161>a Suri<U+0107>|pages=5-19|volume=10|issue=1|month=June|year=2005|accessdate=28 January 2012}}</ref> Remnants of the former are found in the Adriatic Sea itself, as well as in the southern [[Alps]] and the Dinaric Alps, and remnants of the latter are exhibited as the Gargano Promontory and the [[Maiella]] Mountain. In the [[Eocene]] and early [[Oligocene]] the plate moves to the North and Northeast, contributing to [[Alpine orogeny]], specifically orogeny of the Dinarides and the Alps. In [[Chattian|Late Oligocene]], the motion is reversed and the [[Apennine Mountains]] orogeny took place.<ref name="Jura<U+010D>i<U+0107>">{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Zagreb]], Faculty of Science, Geological Department|language=Croatian|title=Geologija mora, Mediteran i Jadran|trans_title=Geology of the sea, Mediterranean and Adriatic|title=Mladen Jura<U+010D>i<U+0107>|accessdate=28 January 2012}}</ref> An unbroken zone of increased seismic activity borders the Adriatic Sea, with a belt of thrust faults generally oriented Northeast&ndash;Southwest on the East coast and Northeast&ndash;Southwest normal faults in the Apennines&mdash;indicating counterclockwise rotation of the Adriatic.<ref>{{cite book|page=352|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=z6h_2UnYIeEC|title=The Adria microplate: GPS geodesy, tectonics and hazards|publisher=Springer|year=2006|isbn=9781402042331|author=Nicholas Pinter|accessdate=28 January 2012}}</ref> An active {{convert|200|km|adj=on}} fault was identified Northwest of Dubrovnik, adding to the Dalmatian islands as the [[Eurasian Plate]] slides over the Adriatic microplate. Furthermore, the fault causes the southern tip of the Apennine peninsula to move towards the opposite shore by about {{convert|0.4|cm|abbr=off}} per year. If that movement continues, the seafloor will be completely consumed and the Adriatic Sea closed off in 50&ndash;70&nbsp;million years.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[National Geographic Society]]|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2008/01/080125-europe-fault.html|title=New Fault Found in Europe; May "Close Up" Adriatic Sea|author=Sara Goudarzi|date=25 January 2008|accessdate=28 January 2012}}</ref>

===Seafloor sediment===
[[File:Spring Runoff in the Adriatic Sea.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Sediment]] billowing out from Italy's shore into the Adriatic.]]
All types of seafloor sediments are found in the Adriatic Sea. Comparably shallow seabed of the Northern Adriatic is characterized by relict sand, while muddy bed is typical at depths below {{convert|100|m|abbr=off}}.<ref name="Adriamed">{{cite web|publisher=FAO AdriaMed|url=http://www.faoadriamed.org/pdf/publications/td13/mmm-td-13.pdf|format=PDF|title=Adriatic Sea Fisheries: outline of some main facts|authors=Piero Mannini, Fabio Massa, Nicoletta Milone|accessdate=29 January 2012}}</ref> There are five [[Geomorphology|geomorphological]] units in the Adriatic: Northern Adriatic (up to {{convert|100|m|abbr=off}} deep), North Adriatic islands area protected against sediments filling it in by outer islands (pre-[[Holocene]] [[karst]] relief), Middle Adriatic islands area (large [[Dalmatia]]n islands), Middle Adriatic (characterized by the Middle Adriatic Depression) and the Southern Adriatic consisting of a coastal [[Continental shelf|shelf]] and the Southern Adriatic Depression. Sediments deposited in the Adriatic Sea today generally originate at the Northwest coast, carried by rivers Po, [[Reno (river)|Reno]], [[Adige]], [[Brenta (river)|Brenta]], [[Tagliamento]], [[Piave (river)|Piave]] and So<U+010D>a. Volume of sediments carried from the Eastern shore by rivers [[Rje<U+010D>ina]], [[Zrmanja]], Krka, [[Cetina]], [[Ombla]], [[Dragonja]], [[Mirna (Croatia)|Mirna]], [[Ra<U+0161>a (river)|Ra<U+0161>a]] and Neretva is negligible as those are largely deposited at the river mouths. The western shores of the Adriatic are largely either [[Flat coast|alluvial]] or [[Marine terrace|terraced]], while the eastern shores are predominantly rocky, except for the southernmost part of the shore located in Albania, which consists of sandy coves and rocky capes.<ref name="Jura<U+010D>i<U+0107>"/>

===Coasts===
The Eastern Adriatic coast, especially between [[Gulf of Trieste]] and [[Bay of Kotor]], is one of the most indented ones. The majority of the eastern coast is characterized by [[karst]] topography, developed from the Adriatic Carbonate Platform. Karstification there largely began after final uplift of the Dinarides in Oligocene and [[Miocene]], when the carbonate deposits were exposed to atmospheric effects, extending to level of {{convert|120|m|abbr=off}} below present sea level, exposed during the [[Last Glacial Maximum]]. It is estimated that some karst formations are related to earlier emersions, most notably the [[Messinian salinity crisis]].<ref name="Suri<U+0107>"/> Similarly, karst developed in [[Apulia]] from the Apulian Carbonate Platform.<ref>{{cite journal|format=PDF|url=http://carsologica.zrc-sazu.si/downloads/401/Parise.pdf|journal=Acta Carsologica|volume=40|issue=1|pages=73-93|year=2011|author=Mario Parise|title=Surface and subsurface karst geomorphology in the Murge (Apulia, Southern Italy)|accessdate=28 January 2012|issn=0583-6050|publisher=[[Slovenian Academy of Sciences and Arts]]}}</ref>

The largest part of the Eastern coast consists of [[carbonate rock]]s, while [[flysch]] is significantly represented in the Gulf of Trieste coast, especially along the Slovenia's coast where {{convert|80|m|adj=on}} [[Strunjan cliff]], the highest on the entire Adriatic coast is located,<ref>{{cite book|page=115|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=KOn0XjYNw_IC|title=Anthology: SEM Institue for Cliamte Change|authors=Timi E<U+0107>imovi<U+0107>, Elmar A. Stuhler, Marjan Vezjak|publisher=Rainer Hampp Verlag|year=2000|isbn=9783879885015|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref> on the [[Kvarner Gulf]] coast opposite Krk, and in Dalmatia north of Split.<ref>{{cite book|pages=146-149|title=Tectonic aspects of the Alpine-Dinaride-Carpathian system|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=864MOs0qeuEC|author=Siegfried Siegesmund|publisher=Geological Society|year=2008|isbn=9781862392526|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref> The same type of rocks are found in Albania,<ref>{{cite book|pages=7-16|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=aYRup5mRcGsC|title=Encyclopedia of European and Asian regional geology|authors=Eldridge M. Moores, Rhodes Whitmore Fairbridge|publisher=Springer|year=1997|isbn=9780412740404|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref> and on the Western Adriatic coast.<ref>{{cite book|pages=6-56|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=qBNr2kdRbTcC|title=Geology and tectonic evolution of the central-southern Apennines, Italy|authors=Livio Vezzani, Andrea Festa, Francesca C. Ghisetti|publisher=Geological Society of America|year=2010|isbn=9780813724690|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref>

There are alternations of maritime and alluvial sediments occurring in Po Valley, at the Northwest coast of the Adriatic, as far west as [[Piacenza]], dating to [[Pleistocene]] as the sea advanced and receded over the valley. An advance began after the Last Glacial Maximum, which brought the Adriatic to a high point at about 5,500 years ago.<ref>{{cite book|chapter=Chapter 6: Pleistocene and Holocene Sediments|title=The northern Adriatic ecosystem: deep time in a shallow sea|first=Frank Kenneth|last= McKinney|edition=illustrated|publisher=Columbia University Press|url=http://books.google.hr/books/about/The_northern_Adriatic_ecosystem.html?id=TuxEf_Yn4YkC|year=2007|isbn=9780231132428|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref> Since then the Po delta had been prograding. The rate of coastal zone progradation between 1000 BC and 1200 AD was {{convert|4|m|abbr=off}} per year.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Distributary channels and their impact on sediment dispersal|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science?_ob=ArticleURL&_udi=B6V6M-4GWBWFT-2&_user=131115&_coverDate=11%2F15%2F2005&_rdoc=1&_fmt=high&_orig=search&_sort=d&_docanchor=&view=c&_searchStrId=1343366263&_rerunOrigin=google&_acct=C000009658&_version=1&_urlVersion=0&_userid=131115&md5=2f586a27a37212d31d722443c048f0aa|author=J.P.M. Syvitski et al.|journal=Marine Geology|volume=222-223|issue=15|pages=75<U+2013>94|doi=10.1016/j.margeo.2005.06.030|year=October, 2005|publisher=[[Elsevier]]|accessdate=2010-05-21}}</ref> In the 12th century, the delta advanced at a rate of {{convert|25|m|abbr=off}} per year. In 1600s, the delta began becoming a human-controlled environment, as excavation of artificial channels started. The channels and new [[Distributary|distributaries]] of Po prograded at rates of {{convert|50|m|abbr=off}} per year or more since.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Theseus Project|url=http://www.theseusproject.eu/wiki/Geological_processes_in_the_Anthropocene:_the_Po_River_Delta|accessdate=28 January 2012|title=Geological processes in the Anthropocene: the Po River Delta}}</ref> There are more than 20 other rivers flowing into the Adriatic Sea also forming alluvial coastlines in Italy alone.<ref>{{cite book|page=210|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=v_45Mb-OJIcC|title=Coastal Aquifers Intrusion Technology: Mediterranean Countries|editor=Juan Antonio L<U+00F3>pez Geta|publisher=Instituto Geol<U+00F3>gico y Minero de Espa<U+00F1>a|year=2003|isbn=9788478404711|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref> There are comparably smaller alluvial coasts of the Eastern Adriatic&mdash;in deltas of [[Dragonja]],<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Government of Slovenia]]|url=http://www.vlada.si/en/about_slovenia/geography/the_slovenian_sea/|title=Slovenian Sea|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref> [[Bojana (river)|Bojana]],<ref>{{cite web|publisher=EURONATUR|url=http://www.euronatur.org/uploads/media/Chapt_1-3_Rapid_assessment_of_the_Ecological_Value_of_the_Bojana-Buna_Delta_01.pdf|format=PDF|title=Rapid assessment of the Ecological Value of the Bojana-Buna Delta|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref> and [[Neretva]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[National Center for Biotechnology Information]]|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2121601/|title=The Neretva Delta: Green Pearl of Coastal Croatia|author=Jasmina Mu<U+017E>ini<U+0107>|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref>

==Flora and fauna==
The Adriatic Sea is unique unit of the Mediterranean in terms of [[biogeography]], particularly because of numerous [[Endemism|endemic]] species. Croatian National Biodiversity Strategy Action Plan identified more than 7,000 animal and plant species in the Adriatic Sea. The Middle Adriatic basin is especially abundant in endemic plant species, with 535 identified species of [[Green algae|green]], [[Brown algae|brown]] and [[red algae]].<ref name="USAID-Bio">{{cite web|publisher=Natural Resources Management & Development Portal|url=http://rmportal.net/library/content/118_croatia/view?searchterm=en|title=Biodiversity assessment for Croatia|date=31 December 2000|author=Chemonics International Inc.|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> Four out of five Mediterranean [[seagrass]] species are found in the Adriatic Sea. The most common species are [[Cymodocea nodosa]] and [[Zostera|Zostera noltii]], while [[Zostera marina]] and [[Posidonia oceanica]] are comparably rare.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Aquatic Botany]]|volume=77|year=2003|pages=17-25|title=Genome size of Adriatic seagrasses|authors=Jasna Dolenc Koce, Barbara Vilhar, Borut Bohanec, Marina Dermastia|accessdate=30 January 2012|url=http://www.vliz.be/imisdocs/publications/57225.pdf|format=PDF|issn=0304-3770}}</ref>

A number of [[Rare species|rare]] and [[threatened species]] are also found along the eastern coast of the Adriatic, and as it is relatively clearer and less polluted compared to the Western Adriatic coast&mdash;in part because the sea currents flow through the Adriatic in counterclockwise direction, thus bringing clearer waters up the Eastern coast and returning as increasingly polluted water down the Western coast. This has significantly contributed to the biodiversity of the countries along the eastern Adriatic coast. The [[common bottlenose dolphin]] is common in the Eastern coast waters only. Approximately thirty species of fish are found only in one or two of the countries bordering Adriatic Sea. Those are particularly related to the karst morphology of the coastal or submarine topography. There are 45 [[subspecies]] endemic to the Adriatic Sea coast and islands. In the Adriatic Sea, there are at least 410 species and subspecies of fish, representing approximately 70% of Mediterranean taxa, with seven species endemic to the Adriatic. 64 species are considered threatened, largely because of overfishing.<ref name="USAID-Bio"/> Only a small fraction of the fish fauna found in the Adriatic is attributed to recent processes such as [[Lessepsian migration]], cases of escape from [[mariculture]] and similar.<ref>{{cite book|publisher=Magnolia Press|url=http://books.google.hr/books/about/Checklist_of_the_Adriatic_Sea_Fishes.html?id=agwskgAACAAJ|title=Checklist of the Adriatic Sea Fishes|author1=Lovrenc Lipej|author2=Jakov Dul<U+010D>i<U+0107>|isbn=9781869775759|year=2010|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref>

===Protected areas===
[[File:Tremiti 00.jpg|thumb|left|[[Isole Tremiti]] protected area]]
Even though marine biodiversity of the Adriatic Sea is relatively high, several [[marine protected area]]s were established by some of the countries along its coasts. In Italy, those are [[Miramare]] in the Gulf of Trieste, in the Northern Adriatic, [[Torre del Cerrano]] and [[Isole Tremiti]] in the Middle Adriatic basin and [[Torre Guaceto]] in southern Apulia.<ref name="EU-Casestudy"/> The Miramare protected area was established in 1986 and covers {{convert|30|ha|abbr=off}} of coast and {{convert|90|ha|abbr=off}} of sea. The area encompasses {{convert|1.8|km|abbr=off}} of coastline near Miramare promontory in the Gulf of Trieste.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=La Riserva Marina di Miramare|url=http://www.riservamarinamiramare.it/riserva/index.htm|title=La Riserva|trans_title=The reserve|language=Italian|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> The Torre Cerrano protected area was created in 2009, extending {{convert|3|nmi|km|abbr=off}} into the sea and along {{convert|7|km|abbr=off}} of coastline. Various zones of the protected area cover {{convert|37|km2|abbr=off}} of sea surface only.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Marine Protected Area Torre Cerrano|url=http://www.torredelcerrano.it/en/the-marine-protected-area.html|title=The Marine Protected Area|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> Isole Tremiti are a protected area since 1989, while the Tremiti islands themselves are a part of the [[Gargano National Park]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=tremiti.eu|url=http://www.tremiti.eu/isole/riserva_marina/parco.aspx|language=Italian|title=Riserva Marina delle Isole Tremiti|trans_title=Tremiti Islands Marine Reserve|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> The Torre Guaceto protected area, located near [[Brindisi]] and [[Carovigno]] covers sea surface of {{convert|2227|ha|abbr=off}} and it is adjacent to Torre Guaceto State Reserve covering {{convert|1114|ha|abbr=off}} of coast and sharing a {{convert|8|km|adj=on}} coastline with the marine protected area.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Consorzio di Gestione di Torre Guaceto|url=http://www.parks.it/riserva.marina.torre.guaceto/Epar.php|title=Protected Area|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> Furthermore there are 10 [[List of Ramsar wetlands of international importance|Ramsar wetland reserves]] in Italy located along the Adriatic coast.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Ramsar Convention]]|url=http://www.ramsar.org/cda/en/ramsar-pubs-annolist-anno-italy/main/ramsar/1-30-168%5E16565_4000_0__|title=The Annotated Ramsar List: Italy|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref>

[[File:Kornati islands.jpg|thumb|right|[[Kornati]] national park]]
There are seven marine protected areas in Croatia: [[Brijuni]] and [[Lim (Croatia)|Lim Canal]] off coast of [[Istria]] peninsula, near [[Pula]] and [[Rovinj]] respectively, [[Kornati]] and [[Tela<U+0161><U+0107>ica]] in the Middle Adriatic basin, near [[<U+0160>ibenik]], and [[Lastovo]], [[Bay of Mali Ston]] ({{lang-hr|Malostonski zaljev}}) and [[Mljet]] in the Southern [[Dalmatia]].<ref name="EU-Casestudy"/> Brijuni [[national park]] encompasses the {{convert|743.3|ha|adj=on}} archipelago itself and {{convert|2651.7|ha|abbr=off}} of surrounding sea.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Brijuni]] national park|url=http://www.brijuni.hr/en/general_info|title=General Info|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> Brijuni became a national park in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Brijuni]] national park|url=http://www.brijuni.hr/en/about_us/documents_and_reports|title=Documents and reports|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> Lim Canal, a {{convert|10|km|adj=on}} [[ria]] of [[Pazin<U+010D>ica]] river.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=City of [[Rovinj]]|url=http://www.rovinj.hr/rovinj/rovinj/priroda/limski-kanal|title=Limski kanal|trans_title=Lim Canal|language=Croatian|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> Kornati national park was established in 1980 and it covers approximately {{convert|220|km2|abbr=off}}, including 89 islands and islets. Still, the marine environment encompasses three quarters of the total area, while length of the island shores combined equals {{convert|238|km|abbr=off}}.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Kornati]] national park|url=http://www.kornati.hr/eng/index.asp#|title=Welcome back to the National Park Kornati|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> Tela<U+0161><U+0107>ica is a nature park established on [[Dugi Otok]] in 1988. The park covers {{convert|69|km|adj=on}} coastline, {{convert|22.95|km2|abbr=off}} of land and {{convert|44.55|km2|abbr=off}} of sea.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Tela<U+0161><U+0107>ica nature park|url=http://www.telascica.hr/opci-podaci.php?lang=en|title=Nature Park Tela<U+0161><U+0107>ica|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> Bay of Mali Ston is located at the border of Croatia and Bosnia and Herzegovina, north of [[Pelje<U+0161>ac]] peninsula. The marine protected are covers {{convert|48|km2|abbr=off}}.<ref name="EU-Casestudy"/> Lastovo nature park was established in 2006, and it includes 44 islands and islets, {{convert|53|km2|abbr=off}} of land and {{convert|143|m2|abbr=off}} of sea surface.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Lastovo nature park|url=http://pp-lastovo.hr/hr/opce-informacije|title=Op<U+0107>e informacije|trans_title=General information|language=Croatian|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> Mljet national park was established in 1960, covering {{convert|24|km2|adj=on}} marine protection area.<ref name="EU-Casestudy"/> In addition, there is a Ramsar wetland reserve in Croatia&mdash;Neretva River delta.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Ramsar Convention]]|url=http://www.ramsar.org/cda/en/ramsar-pubs-annolist-anno-croatia/main/ramsar/1-30-168%5E16461_4000_0__|title=The Annotated Ramsar List: Croatia|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref>

There are six marine and coastal protected areas in Slovenia: the [[Cape Madona]], the [[Fiesa Lakes]], and the [[Debeli Rti<U+010D>]] natural monuments; the [[Se<U+010D>ovlje Salina Nature Park|Se<U+010D>ovlje Salina]] and the [[Strunjan Nature Park|Strunjan]] nature parks, and the [[<U+0160>kocjan Inlet Natural Reserve|<U+0160>kocjan Inlet]] natural reserve.<ref>{{cite article |url=http://www.zrsvn.si/dokumenti/63/2/2011/Vidmar_Turk_2538.pdf |title=Marine Protected Areas in Slovenia: How Far are We From the 2012/2020 Target? |authors=Vidmar, Barbara. Turk, Robert |journal=Varstvo narave |year=2011 |month=September |issue=Suppl. 1 |page=163 |publisher=Institute of the Republic of Slovenia for Nature Conservation}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zrsvn.si/sl/informacija.asp?id_meta_type=63&id_informacija=651 |title=Naravni spomenik Jezeri v Fiesi |language=Slovene |trans_title=The Fiesa Lakes Natural Monument |publisher=Institute of the Republic of Slovenia for Nature Conservation |accessdate=4 February 2012}}</ref> In addition, the area of the [[Se<U+010D>ovlje salt pans]], covering {{convert|650|m2|abbr=on}}, has been a Ramsar wetland since 1993.<ref>{{cite article |url=http://www.uradni-list.si/files/RS_-2011-053-02504-OB~P001-0000.PDF |title=Krajinski park Se<U+010D>oveljske soline: na<U+010D>rt upravljanja 2011<U+2013>2021 |language=Slovene |trans_title=The Se<U+010D>ovlje Salina Nature Park: Management Plan 2011<U+2013>2012 |date=1 July 2011 |newspaper=Official Gazette of the Republic of Slovenia |issue=53 |page=14}}</ref> In 2010, Albania established its first marine protection area of the [[Karaburun-Sazan National Marine Park]] at the [[Karaburun Peninsula, Albania|Karaburun Peninsula]], where the Adriatic and the Ionian seas meet. The park covers a total of {{convert|12570|ha|abbr=off}}.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=shqiperia.com|url=http://lajme.shqiperia.com/lajme/artikull/iden/1046857853/titulli/VENDIM-PER-SHPALLJEN-PARK-KOMBETAR-TE-EKOSISTEMIT-NATYROR-DETAR-PRANE-GADISHULLIT-TE--KARABURUNIT-DHE-ISHULLIT-TE-SAZANIT#minimize|title=VENDIM P<U+00CB>R SHPALLJEN <U+201C>PARK KOMB<U+00CB>TAR<U+201D> T<U+00CB> EKOSISTEMIT NATYROR DETAR PRAN<U+00CB> GADISHULLIT T<U+00CB> KARABURUNIT DHE ISHULLIT T<U+00CB> SAZANIT|language=Albanian|trans_title=Decision to declare "NATIONAL PARK" TO THE MARITIME natural ecosystem Karaburun Peninsula and the island of Sazan|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> Two additional marine protection areas are planned in Albania: [[Cape of Rodon]] ({{lang-al|Kepi i Rodonit}}) and [[Porto Palermo]].<ref name="EU-Casestudy"/> In addition, Albania is home to two Ramsar wetland reserves<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Ramsar Convention]]|url=http://www.ramsar.org/cda/en/ramsar-pubs-annolist-annotated-ramsar-17050/main/ramsar/1-30-168%5E17050_4000_0__|title=The Annotated Ramsar List: Albania|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref> Neither Bosnia and Herzegovina nor Montenegro plan to establish any marine protection areas.<ref name="EU-Casestudy"/>

==History==
===Name===
Etymology of the Adriatic Sea is linked to [[Etruscan civilization|Etruscan]] settlement of [[Adria]], itself probably originating from [[Illyrian languages|Illyrian]] word ''adur'' meaning water or sea.<ref>{{cite book|page=20|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=M1JIPAN-eJ4C|title=Placenames of the world|author=Adrian Room|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|isbn=9780786422487|year=2006|accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref> In classical antiquity, the sea was known as ''Mare Adriaticum'' (''Mare Hadriaticum'', also sometimes simplified to ''Adria'') or, less frequently, as ''Mare Superum''.<ref>{{cite book|page=504|publisher=F. and C. Rivington|year=1812|title=The British Critic, volume 40|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=EQEwAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref> The two terms were not synonymous, however. ''Mare Adriaticum'' generally corresponds to extent of the Adriatic Sea, spanning from the [[Gulf of Venice]] to the Strait of Otranto. That boundary became more consistently defined by Roman authors&mdash;early Greek sources place boundary between the Adriatic and [[Ionian Sea]]s at various places ranging from adjacent to the Gulf of Venice to the southern tip of [[Peloponnese]], eastern shores of [[Sicily]] and western shores of [[Crete]].<ref>{{cite book|pages=53-54|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=LOhSAAAAYAAJ|title=Calmet's dictionary of the Holy Bible|author1=Augustin Calmet|author2=Charles Taylor|year=1830|accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref> ''Mare Superum'' on the other hand normally encompassed modern Adriatic Sea and the sea off the southern coast of Apennine peninsula, as far as the [[Strait of Sicily]].<ref>{{cite book|page=20|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=Wn949Sr-POkC|title=A Classical Dictionary: Containing the Principle Proper Names Mentioned in Ancient Authors|author=[[Charles Anthon]]|isbn=9781417976546|publisher=[[Kessinger Publishing]]|year=2005|accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref> Another name used in the period was ''Mare Dalmaticum'', applied to waters off coast of [[Dalmatia (Roman province)|Dalmatia]] or [[Illyricum (Roman province)|Illyricum]].<ref>{{cite book|page=380|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=NZgMAQAAMAAJ|title=The Germania and Agricola, and also selections from the Annals, of Tacitus|author=[[Cornelius Tacitus]]|editor=Charles Anthon|publisher=[[Harper (publisher)|Harper]]|year=1853|accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref>

===Early history===
[[File:Pula Arena aerial 1.jpg|thumb|right|[[Pula Arena]], one of the six largest surviving Roman amphitheatres]]
Settlements along the Adriatic appear in [[Albania]] and [[Dalmatia]] on the eastern coast dating to between 6100 and 5900 BC, related to the [[Cardium Pottery|Cardium Pottery Culture]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Europe Between the Oceans|author=[[Barry Cunliffe]]|year=2008|pages=115-116|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=nHUEAQAAIAAJ|isbn= 9780300119237|publisher=[[Yale University Press]]|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> During the [[Classical Antiquity]] the shores of the Adriatic were initially inhabited by the [[Ancient peoples of Italy]]&mdash;among whom the [[Etruscan civilization]] becoming the most prominent before rise of the [[Roman Republic]]&mdash;on the Western Adriatic coast,<ref>{{cite book|pages=2-14|title=Etruscan Italy|author=John Franklin Hall|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=1996|isbn=9780842523349|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=bUhT7i7XhOAC|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> and by the [[Illyria]]ns along the Eastern Adriatic coast.<ref>{{cite book|page=91-104|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=4Nv6SPRKqs8C|title=The Illyrians|author=John Wilkes|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|year=1995|isbn=9780631198079|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> [[Classical Greece|Greek]] colonisation of the Adriatic dates back to the 7th and the 6th century BC when [[Epidamnus]] and [[Apollonia (Illyria)|Apollonia]] were founded. Greeks soon expanded further north establishing several cities, including [[Epidaurus (Dalmatia)|Epidaurus]], [[Black Corcyra]], [[Vis (island)|Issa]] and [[Ancona]], with trade established as far North as the Po River delta, where [[emporion]] of Adria was founded. Following the Roman intervention and the [[Illyrian Wars]], the Eastern Adriatic shore became a [[Illyricum (Roman province)|province of the Roman Republic]].<ref>{{cite book|pages=155-186|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=z3C9b4FvpEwC|title=Greek colonisation|author=Gocha R. Tsetskhladze|publisher=BRILL|year=2008|isbn= 9789004155763|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> The initial intervention in 229 BC marked the first time that the [[Roman navy]] crossed the Adriatic to launch a military campaign.<ref>{{cite book|page=359|title=The Hellenistic world and the coming of Rome|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=EkdCokrrp4gC|author=Erich S. Gruen|publisher=University of California Press|year=1986|isbn=9780520057371|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> In [[Middle Ages]], after the [[decline of the Roman Empire]], coasts of the Adriatic were ruled by [[Ostrogoths]], [[Kingdom of the Lombards|Lombards]],<ref>{{cite book|pages=326-328|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=zt3jZ69vJKQC|title=History of the Lombards|author=[[Paul the Deacon]]|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|year=1974|isbn=9780812210798|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> and the [[Byzantine Empire]].<ref>{{cite book|pages=126-130|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=dw3FEpOUrRkC|title=A history of the Ostrogoths|author=Thomas S. Burns|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=1991|isbn=9780253206008|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> The last part of the [[Early Middle Ages]] saw rise of the [[Carolingian Empire]] and subsequent [[Kingdom of Italy (medieval)|Frankish Kingdom of Italy]] which controlled the Western coast of the Adriatic Sea,<ref>{{cite book|page=773|title=A history of all nations, from the earliest periods to the present time|author=Samuel Griswold Goodrich|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=YU3TAAAAMAAJ|publisher=Miller, Orton & Mulligan|year=1856|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> while the Byzantine control of the opposite coast gradually shrunk following [[Eurasian Avars|Avar]] and [[Principality of Littoral Croatia|Croatian]] invasions starting in the 7th century.<ref name="AAPatton">{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=E_NBAAAAYAAJ|title=Researches on the Danube and the Adriatic|author=Andrew Archibald Paton|year=1861|pages=218<U+2013>219|publisher=Tr<U+00FC>bner|accessdate=15 October 2011}}</ref> [[Republic of Venice]] was founded in the period, and it later became a significant trading power after receiving Byzantine tax exemption in 1082.<ref>{{cite book|pages=61-74|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=mQL_EzSne5oC|title=Great history of Venice|publisher=Giunti Editore|isbn= 9788844005917|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> The end of the period brought about [[Holy Roman Empire]]'s control over the Kingdom of Italy which would last until the [[Peace of Westphalia]] in 1648,<ref>{{cite book|pages=188-190|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=LZuxGsXVPoMC|title=African Foreign Policy and Diplomacy|author=Daniel Don Nanjira|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2010|isbn= 9780313379826|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> establishment of an independent [[Kingdom of Croatia (medieval)|Kingdom of Croatia]],<ref name="Posavec">{{cite journal|journal=Radovi Zavoda za hrvatsku povijest|volume=30|issue=1|issn=0353-295X|pages=281<U+2013>290|title=Povijesni zemljovidi i granice Hrvatske u Tomislavovo doba|trans_title= Historical maps and borders of Croatia in age of Tomislav|language=Croatian|author=Vladimir Posavec|year=1998|month=March|accessdate=16 October 2011|url=http://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=62779}}</ref> and Byzantine Empire expanded to the Southern Apennine peninsula.<ref name=Norwich-250>Norwich, pp. 250&ndash;253</ref> Furthermore, the [[Papal States]] were carved out in areas around [[Rome]] in the 8th century.<ref>{{cite book|pages=296-298|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=cY1SymrAGeEC|title=The church triumphant|author=E. Glenn Hinson|publisher=Mercer University Press|year=1995|isbn= 9780865544369|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref>

[[File:Venezia Riva degli Schiavoni 002.JPG|thumb|left|[[Venice]] was a leading trading power in Europe]]
[[High Middle Ages]] in the Adriatic Sea basin saw further territorial changes, including the [[Norman conquest of southern Italy]] ending Byzantine presence on the Apennine peninsula in the 11th and the 12th centuries,<ref>{{cite book|pages=3-5|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=c_Pft6RqfYIC|title=The Norman conquest of Southern Italy and Sicily|author=Gordon S. Brown|publisher=McFarland|year=2003|isbn= 9780786414727|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref>, and the territory would become the [[Kingdom of Naples]] in 1282,<ref>{{cite book | last = Fremont-Barnes | first = Gregory | url=http://books.google.hr/books/about/Encyclopedia_of_the_age_of_political_rev.html?id=6_2wkP4j-EsC&redir_esc=y|title = Encyclopedia of the Age of Political Revolutions and New Ideologies, 1760-1815: Volume 1 | publisher=Greenwood | year = 2007| page = 495 | isbn = 978-0313334467}}</ref> and control of a substantial part of the Eastern Adriatic coast by the [[Kingdom of Hungary in the Middle Ages|Kingdom of Hungary]] after a [[personal union]] was established between Croatia and Hungary in 1102.<ref name="HR-HU-Heka">{{cite journal|journal=Scrinia Slavonica|issn=1332-4853|publisher=Hrvatski institut za povijest <U+2013> Podru<U+017E>nica za povijest Slavonije, Srijema i Baranje|title= Hrvatsko-ugarski odnosi od sredinjega vijeka do nagodbe iz 1868. s posebnim osvrtom na pitanja Slavonije|trans_title=Croatian-Hungarian relations from the Middle Ages to the Compromise of 1868, with a special survey of the Slavonian issue|language=Croatian|url=http://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=68144|author= Ladislav Heka|year=2008|month=October|volume=8|issue=1|pages=152<U+2013>173|accessdate=16 October 2011}}</ref> In the period, the Republic of Venice began to expand its territory and influence.<ref name=Norwich-72>Norwich, p. 72</ref> In 1202, the [[Fourth Crusade]] was diverted to conquer [[Siege of Zara|Zadar]] on behest of Venetians&mdash;the first instance of a [[Crusades|Crusader force]] attacking a [[Catholic]] city&mdash;before proceeding to sack [[Constantinople]].<ref>{{cite book|page=43-54|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=5M7nwV0DvBYC|title=The souls of Venice|author=Janet Sethre|publisher=McFarland|year=2003|isbn=9780786415731|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> In the century, Venice established itself as one of the leading [[Economic history of Venice|trading nations]]. During much of the 12th and the 13th century, Venice and the [[Republic of Genoa]] were engaged in [[Venetian<U+2013>Genoese Wars]] ending in [[War of Chioggia|War]] and [[Battle of Chioggia]], removing Geonoese from the Adriatic.<ref>{{cite book|pages=118-119|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=xMZI2QEer9QC|title=Civilization and Capitalism, 15th-18th Century|author=Fernand Braudel|publisher=University of California Press|year=1992|isbn=9780520081161|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> Still, the Treaty of Turin of 1381 that ended the war required Venice to renounce claims to Dalmatia, after losing the territory to Hungary in 1358. In the same year, the [[Republic of Dubrovnik]] was established a city-state as it escaped Venetian suzerainty.<ref>{{cite book|page=48|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=Xd422lS6ezgC|title=History of the Ottoman Empire and Modern Turkey|author=Stanford J. Shaw|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1976|isbn=9780521291637|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> Venice regained Dalmatia in 1409 and held it for nearly four hundred years&mdash;reaching the republic's apex of power in the first half of the 15th century.<ref name="Crouzet">{{cite book|pages=69-82|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=B7gzrJDlUv8C|title=Venice Triumphant|author1=Elisabeth Crouzet-Pavan|author2=Lydia G. Cochrane|publisher=JHU Press|year=2005|isbn=9780801881893|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> The 15th and the 16th centuries brought about destruction of the Byzantine Empire (1453),<ref>{{cite book|page=133|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=qp8ocRg7r2sC|title=The Byzantine Empire|author=Robert Browning|isbn= 9780813207544|publisher=CUA Press|year=1992|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> expansion of the [[Ottoman Empire]] which reached Adriatic shores in present-day Albania and Montenegro,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Reinert|first=Stephen W.|editor=Cyril Mango|title=The Oxford History of Byzantium|url=http://books.google.com/?id=Z6-kHUyyUIsC|location=Oxford|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=270|year=2002|isbn=0198140983|chapter=Fragmentation (1204<U+2013>1453)}}</ref> as well as immediate hinterland of Dalmatian coast, defeating the Hungarian and Croatian armies at [[Battle of Krbava field|Krbava]] (1493) and [[Battle of Moh<U+00E1>cs|Moh<U+00E1>cs]] (1526).<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=lVBB1a0rC70C|author=Richard C. Frucht|title=Eastern Europe: An Introduction to the People, Lands, and Culture|year=2005|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn= 9781576078006|accessdate=18 October 2011|pages=422-423}}</ref> Those defeats spelled the end of an independent Hungarian kingdom, and both [[Parliament on Cetin|Croatian]] and [[Kingdom of Hungary (1538<U+2013>1867)|Hungarian]] nobility chose [[Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor|Ferdinand I]] of the [[House of Habsburg]] as the new ruler and bringing the [[Habsburg Monarchy]] to the shore of Adriatic Sea, where it will remain for nearly four hundred years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sabor.hr/Default.aspx?sec=404|title=Povijest saborovanja|trans_title=History of parliamentarism|language=Croatian|publisher=[[Sabor]]|accessdate=18 October 2010}}</ref> The Ottomans and the Venetians fought a [[Ottoman<U+2013>Venetian Wars|series of wars]], but until the 17th century, those were not fought in the Adriatic area.<ref name="Crouzet"/> The Ottoman raids of the Adriatic coasts were effectively stopped after the [[Battle of Lepanto]] (1571) fought south of the Strait of Otranto.<ref>{{cite book|page=495|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=u6w8AAAAIAAJ|title=The Cambridge modern history|publisher=CUP Archive|authors=G. W. Prothero et al.|year=1934|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref>

===Age of sail===
[[File:Battle of Lissa.jpg|thumb|right|[[Battle of Lissa (1811)|Battle of Lissa]], 1811]]
In 1648, the Holy Roman Empire lost its claim on the Italian lands, formally ending the Kingdom of Italy, however its only outlet on the Adriatic Sea, the [[Duchy of Ferrara]] was already lost to the Papal States.<ref>{{cite book|page=202|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=irQ5DKF69HwC|title=The Renaissance in Europe|author=Margaret L. King|publisher=Laurence King Publishing|year=2003|isbn=9781856693745|accessdate=31 January 2011}}</ref> The final territorial changes of the 17th century were caused by the [[Morean War|Morean or the Sixth Ottoman-Venetian War]], when Venice slightly enlarged its possessions in Dalmatia in 1699.<ref>{{cite book|page=66|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=T3Sg_1wR4poC|title=The Peace of Passarowitz, 1718|author1=Charles Ingrao|author2=Nikola Samard<U+017E>i<U+0107>|author3=Jovan Pesalj|publisher=Purdue University Press|year=2011|isbn=9781557535948|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> In 1797, the Republic of Venice was abolished after [[Napoleonic Wars|French conquest]] (1797).<ref>{{cite book|page=219|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=PJEhbcRSELwC|title=Venice reconsidered|author1=John Jeffries Martin|author2=Dennis Romano|publisher=JHU Press|year=2002|isbn=9780801873089|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> The Venetian territory was then handed over to [[Venetian Province|Austria]] and briefly ruled as a part of [[Archduchy of Austria]]. The territory was turned back to France after the [[Peace of Pressburg]] (1805) when the territory in the Po Valley became an integral part of new [[Kingdom of Italy (Napoleonic)|Kingdom of Italy]].<ref name="Venetian Province">{{cite book|pages=192, 245|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=PVh4b1_YmskC|title=Europe|publisher=Forgotten Books|isbn=9781440062179|author=H. Morse Stephens|year=2010|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> The Kingdom included [[Romagna]] province thus removing the Papal State from the Adriatic coast,<ref>{{cite book|page=1103|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=7VDcmDeLuV4C|title=The Papacy: Gaius-Proxies|author=Philippe Levillain|publisher=[[Routledge]]|year=2002|isbn=9780415922302|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> but Trieste, Istria and Dalmatia were made a separate province of the [[First French Empire|French Empire]]&mdash;the [[Illyrian Provinces]].<ref name="Venetian Province"/> The Illyrian Provinces were created in 1809 through the [[Treaty of Sch<U+00F6>nbrunn]] and they represented the end of Venetian rule on the East Adriatic coast, as well as the end of existence of the Republic of Dubrovnik.<ref>{{cite book|pages=188-194|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=aW3aMxd5vrkC|title=Napoleon and the transformation of Europe|author=Alexander I. Grab|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2003|isbn=9780333682746|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> The Adriatic Sea was a minor [[Theater (warfare)|theatre of war]] during the Napoleonic Wars, as the [[Adriatic campaign of 1807<U+2013>1814]] involved [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British]] [[Royal Navy]] contesting control of the Adriatic by the combined navies of France, Italy and Kingdom of Naples. During the campaign, the Royal Navy occupied [[Vis (island)|Vis]] and established its base there in [[Vis (town)|Port St. George]].<ref>{{cite book|page=112|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=TH_fAAAAMAAJ|title=The frigates|author=James Henderson|publisher=Leo Cooper|year=1994|isbn= 9780850524321|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> The campaign reached its climax in the [[Battle of Lissa (1811)|Battle of Lissa]] in 1811,<ref>{{cite book|page=425|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=uybAm7NaF5YC|title=Searching for the Forgotten War - 1812 Canada|author1=Patrick Richard Carstens|author2=Timothy L Sanford|publisher=Xlibris Corporation|year=2011|isbn=9781453588901|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> and ended in British troops and [[Austrian Empire|Austrian]] army seizing the Eastern Adriatic coast cities from the French.<ref>{{cite book|page=180|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=BH1nAAAAMAAJ|title=The Naval History of Great Britain, Volume 6, 1811<U+2013>1827|author1=William M. James|author2=Andrew D. Lambert|publisher=Conway Maritime|year=2002|isbn=9780851779102|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> Days before the battle of Waterloo, the [[Congress of Vienna]] awarded the Illyrian Provinces spanning from the [[Gulf of Trieste]] to the Bay of Kotor to Austria.<ref>{{cite book|pages=180, 226|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=ZTC3IWC_py8C|title=The Congress of Vienna|author1=Harold Nicolson|author2=Sir Harold Nicolson|publisher=Grove Press|year=2000|isbn=9780802137449|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> The Congress of Vienna also created the [[Kingdom of Lombardy<U+2013>Venetia]], encompassing the city of Venice, surrounding coast and substantial hinterland&mdash;ruled by Austria.<ref>{{cite book|page=200|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=JOTFCTYSjicC|title=Diglossia and power|author=Rosita Rindler Schjerve|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|year=2003|isbn=9783110176544|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> In the south of the Apennine peninsula, the [[Kingdom of the Two Sicilies]] was formed in 1816 through a union of the Kingdom of Naples and the [[Kingdom of Sicily]].<ref>{{cite book|page=601|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=xhoLorFC1iwC|title=Italy|author=Roland Sarti|publisher=Infobase Publishing|year=2004|isbn=9780816045228|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref>

===From ironclads to dreadnoughts===
[[File:Die Seeschlacht bei Lissa.jpg|thumb|left|[[Battle of Lissa (1866)|Battle of Lissa]], 1866]]
Process of [[Italian unification]] culminated in the [[Second Italian War of Independence]] resulting in [[Kingdom of Sardinia]] annexing all territories along the Western Adriatic coast south of [[Venetia (region)|Venetia]] in 1860, and establishment of the [[Kingdom of Italy (1861<U+2013>1946)|Kingdom of Italy]] in 1861 in its place. The Kingdom of Italy expanded in 1866. It [[Third Italian War of Independence|annexed Venetia]],<ref>{{cite book|pages=619-622|title=Western Civilization: Beyond Boundaries|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=e5b57HtZH0kC|authors=Thomas F. X. Noble, Barry S. Strauss, Duane J. Osheim, Kristen B. Neuschel, Elinor Ann Accampo|publisher=Cengage Learning|year=2010|isbn=9781424069620|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> but [[Regia Marina]] was defeated in the Adriatic near [[Battle of Lissa (1866)|Vis]].<ref>{{cite book|pages=73-76|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=kMXURN7sxh4C|title=The Italians of Dalmatia|author=Luciano Monzali|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=2009|isbn=9780802096210|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> Following the [[Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867]] and [[Croatian<U+2013>Hungarian Settlement]] of 1868, control of much of the Eastern Adriatic coast was redefined. [[Cisleithania]]n part of the [[Austria-Hungary]] spanned from [[Austrian Littoral]] to the Bay of Kotor, with exception of the [[Croatian Littoral]]. A [[Corpus separatum (Fiume)|Corpus separatum]] formed in 1779 and containing the city of [[Rijeka]] directly subjected to the [[Lands of the Crown of Saint Stephen|Kingdom of Hungary]] was confirmed and the rest was a part of the [[Kingdom of Croatia-Slavonia]], which in turn was also in the [[Transleithania]]n part of the dual monarchy.<ref name="HR-HU-Heka"/> Length of the Adriatic coastline controlled by the Ottoman Empire shrunk in 1878 when the [[Congress of Berlin]] recognized independence of the [[Principality of Montenegro]] controlling the coast south of Bay of Kotor to [[Bojana (river)|Bojana River]].<ref>{{cite book|page=225|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=sJJWEnXTHdIC|title=The Serbs|author=Sima M. <U+0106>irkovi<U+0107>|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=2004|isbn=9780631204718|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> The Ottoman Empire was completely removed from the Adriatic following the [[First Balkan War]] and consequent [[Treaty of London (1913)|Treaty of London of 1913]] which established independent Albania.<ref>{{cite book|page=1553|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=h5_tSnygvbIC|title=A global chronology of conflict|author=Spencer Tucker|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2009|isbn=9781851096671|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref>

[[File:Novaral.jpg|thumb|right|[[SMS Novara (1913)|SMS ''Novara'']] after [[Battle of the Strait of Otranto (1917)|Battle of the Strait of Otranto]], 1917]]
[[World War I]] [[Adriatic Campaign of World War I|Adriatic Campaign]] was largely limited to attempts of blockade of the sea by the [[Allies of World War I|Allies]] and [[Central Powers]]' [[Battle of the Strait of Otranto (1917)|attempts]] to break it.<ref>{{cite book|page=39|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=2YqjfHLyyj8C|title=World War I|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2005|isbn=9781851094202|accessdate=1 February 2012|editor=Spencer C. Tucker}}</ref> Italy joined the Allies in 1915 after the [[Treaty of London (1915)|Treaty of London]] promised it acquisition of the Austrian Littoral, Northern Dalmatia, port of [[Vlor<U+00EB>]], most East Adriatic islands and establishment of a protectorate in Albania.<ref>{{cite book|page=440|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=EHI3PCjDtsUC|title=The European powers in the First World War|author1=Spencer Tucker|author2=Laura Matysek Wood|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=1996|isbn=9780815303992|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> In 1918, Montenegrin national assembly voted to form an union with the [[Kingdom of Serbia]], giving the latter access to the Adriatic.<ref>{{cite book|page=298|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=ke3EOOUq3gwC|title=Victory 1918|author=Alan Palmer|publisher=Grove Press|year=2000|isbn=9780802137876|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> Another short-lived, unrecognized state established in 1918 was the [[State of Slovenes, Croats and Serbs]] out of parts of Austria-Hungary, comprising most of the coastline of the former monarchy. Later that year, the two formed the [[Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes]]&mdash;subsequently renamed to Yugoslavia. Proponents of the new union in the [[Parliament of Croatia]] at the time saw the move as a defence against Italian expansionism and provisions of the Treaty of London.<ref>Tomasevich, pp. 4&ndash;16</ref> The treaty was largely disregarded by the Britain and [[French Third Republic|France]] because of conflicting promises made to Serbia and perceived lack of Italian contribution to the war effort outside Italy itself.<ref>{{cite book|pages=4-16|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=PNHxISN-dmQC|title=Italian foreign policy in the interwar period, 1918-1940|author=H. James Burgwyn|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|year=1997|isbn=9780275948771|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> The [[Treaty of Saint-Germain-en-Laye (1919)|Treaty of Saint-Germain-en-Laye]] of 1919 did transfer the Austrian Littoral and Istria to Italy, but awarded Dalmatia to Yugoslavia.<ref>{{cite book|page=318|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=Fln44TTgDLIC|title=Europe, 1890-1945|author=Stephen J. Lee|publisher=Routledge|year=2003|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> Following the war, a [[Gabriele d'Annunzio|private force]] of demobilized Italian soldiers seized Rijeka and set up [[Italian Regency of Carnaro]], seen as harbinger of [[Fascism]], in order to force recognition of Italian claim to the city.<ref>{{cite book|pages=127-128|title=Rome in America|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=U9wNxgCo7ycC|author=Peter R. D'Agostino|publisher=Univ of North Carolina Press|year=2004|isbn=9780807855157|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> After sixteen months of its existence, the [[Treaty of Rapallo (1920)|Treaty of Rapallo]] of 1920 redefined Italian&ndash;Yugoslav borders, inter alia transferring  Zadar and islands of Cres, [[Lastovo]] and [[Palagru<U+017E>a]] to Italy, securing the island of Krk for Yugoslavia and establishing the [[Free State of Fiume]]. The Free State of Fiume was abolished in 1924 by the [[Treaty of Rome (1924)|Treaty of Rome]] which awarded Rijeka to Italy and [[Su<U+0161>ak, Rijeka|Su<U+0161>ak]] to Yugoslavia.<ref>{{cite book|pages=135-137|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=qTLSZ3ucaZMC|title=A short history of the Yugoslav peoples|author=Frederick Bernard Singleton|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1985|isbn=9780521274852|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref>

===Modern era===
[[File:Boundary between Italy and Free Territory of Trieste.png|thumb|left|Boundary between [[Free Territory of Trieste]] and [[Italy]]]]
In the [[World War II]], the [[Adriatic Campaign of World War II|Adriatic saw limited naval action]] starting with [[Italian invasion of Albania|Italian invasion]] of [[Albanian Kingdom (1939<U+2013>1943)|Albania]] and [[Axis powers|Axis]] [[Invasion of Yugoslavia]]. The latter resulted in annexation of a large part of Dalmatia and nearly all East Adriatic islands to Italy and establishment of [[puppet state]]s of [[Independent State of Croatia]] and [[Kingdom of Montenegro (1941<U+2013>1944)|Kingdom of Montenegro]] controlling the remainder of former Yugoslav Adriatic coast.<ref>Tomasevich, pp. 130&ndash;139, 233&ndash;234</ref> In 1947, after the [[Armistice between Italy and Allied armed forces]] and the end of the war, Italy, now a [[Italian constitutional referendum, 1946|republic]], and [[Allies of World War II]] signed [[Treaty of Peace with Italy, 1947|Treaty of Peace with Italy]] reversing all wartime annexations, transferring islands of Cres, Lastovo and Palagru<U+017E>a, the cities of Zadar and Rijeka, Istria and most of [[Slovenian Littoral]] to [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|communist Yugoslavia]], guaranteeing independence of Albania and carving out [[Free Territory of Trieste]] (FTT) as a city-state.<ref name="Klemen<U+010D>i<U+010D>">{{cite book|pages=198-202|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=ORSMBFwjAKcC|title=The former Yugoslavia's diverse peoples|author1=Matja<U+017E> Klemen<U+010D>i<U+010D>|author=2Mitja <U+017D>agar|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2004|isbn=9781576072943|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> The FTT was partitioned in 1954 as Trieste itself and area to the North of it were placed under Italian and the rest under Yugoslav control. The arrangement was made permanent by the [[Treaty of Osimo]] in 1975.<ref>{{cite book|pages=141-142|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=TznfHevgsEcC|title=The land and the spirit of Italy|author=John J. Navone|publisher=Legas / Gaetano Cipolla|year=1996|isbn=9781881901129|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref>

During the [[Cold War]], the Adriatic Sea became the southern flank of the [[Iron Curtain]] as Italy allied itself with [[NATO]],<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[NATO]]|title=History|url=http://www.nato.int/history/index.html|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> while the [[Warsaw Pact]] established bases in Albania.<ref>{{cite book|pages=169-170|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=7cDN8q2RHGMC|title=Submarines of the Russian and Soviet navies, 1718-1990|author1=Norman Polmar|author2=Jurrien Noot|publisher=Naval Institute Press|year=1991|isbn=9780870215704|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> After the [[fall of communism]], [[Breakup of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia broke apart]] as [[Ten-Day War|Slovenia]] and [[Croatian independence referendum, 1991|Croatia declared independence]] in 1991,<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1991/06/26/world/2-yugoslav-states-vote-independence-to-press-demands.html?ref=croatia|title=2 Yugoslav States Vote Independence to Press Demands|author=[[Chuck Sudetic]]|date=26 June 1991|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> and Bosnia and Herzegovina followed in 1992,<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[BBC News]]|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/1066981.stm|title=Bosnia-Hercegovina timeline|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> while Montenegro remained in a federation with Serbia, subsequently renamed to [[Serbia and Montenegro]].<ref name="MNE-Timeline">{{cite web|publisher=[[BBC News]]|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/country_profiles/5075632.stm|title=Timeline: Montenegro|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> The [[Croatian War of Independence]] that ensued included limited naval engagement and maritime blockade of Croatian coast by the [[Yugoslav Navy]],<ref>{{cite book|pages=21-25|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=KoHQEEDzL5AC|title=The modern Yugoslav conflict 1991-1995|author=Brendan O'Shea|publisher=Routledge|year=2005|isbn=9780415357050|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> resulting in the [[Battle of the Dalmatian channels]] and withdrawal of Yugoslav vessels.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Slobodna Dalmacija]]|url=http://arhiv.slobodnadalmacija.hr/20041115/temedana01.asp|title=Admiral Letica je naredio: Raspali!|language=Croatian|trans_title=Admiral Letica ordered: Fire!|author=Stjepan Bernardi<U+0107>|date=15 November 2004|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> Montenegro declared its independence in 2006, ending Yugoslav control of any portion of the Adriatic coast.<ref name="MNE-Timeline"/> The period also saw Adriatic Sea as the theatre of several NATO operations, including [[Operation Maritime Guard|blockade of Yugoslavia]],<ref>{{cite web|author=John Pike |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/ops/maritime_guard.htm |title=Operation Maritime Guard |publisher=Globalsecurity.org |accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref>, [[NATO intervention in Bosnia and Herzegovina|intervention in Bosnia and Herzegovina]],<ref>{{cite news|author=Roger Cohen|title=NATO and the UN quarrel in Bosnia as Serbs press on|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1994/11/27/world/nato-and-the-un-quarrel-in-bosnia-as-serbs-press-on.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=27 November 1994|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> and [[1999 NATO bombing of Yugoslavia|bombing of Yugoslavia]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[BBC News]]|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/310748.stm|title=Heart of Belgrade bombed|date=3 April 1999|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref>

==Boundaries==
[[File:TrattatoDiOsimo.jpg|thumb|right|Signing ceremony of the Treaty of Osimo, 10 November 1975]]
Italy and Yugoslavia defined their delimitation of the continental shelf in the Adriatic Sea in 1968,<ref>{{cite book|pages=11-13|url=http://books.google.hr/books?id=lLVFW0an7NUC|title=The maritime boundaries of the Adriatic Sea|authors=Gerald Henry Blake, Du<U+0161>ko Topalovi<U+0107>, Clive H. Schofield|publisher=IBRU|year=1996|isbn=9781897643228|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> with an additional agreement on the boundary in the Gulf of Trieste signed in 1975 pursuant to the Treaty of Osimo. The boundary agreed in 1968 extends {{convert|353|nmi|abbr=off}} and consists of 43&nbsp;points connected by straight lines or circular arc segments. The boundary agreed upon in 1975 consists of 5&nbsp;points, extending from an end point of the 1968 line. All successor states of the former Yugoslavia accepted the agreements. In the southernmost areas of the Adriatic the border was not determined in order to avoid prejudicing location of [[tripoint]] with the Albanian continental shelf border, which remains undefined. Prior to breakup of Yugoslavia, Albania, Italy and Yugoslavia initially proclaimed {{convert|15|nmi|adj=on}} [[territorial waters]], subsequently reduced to {{convert|12|nmi|abbr=off}} and all sides adopted [[Baseline (sea)|baseline]] systems. Most of these were introduced in 1970s. Albania and Italy determined their border at the sea in 1992 on [[equidistance principle]].<ref name="Geoadria-Borders">{{cite journal|journal=Geoadria|publisher=[[University of Zadar]]|issn=1331-2294|url=http://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=71443|title=The maritime boundaries of the Adriatic Sea|author1=Mladen Klemen<U+010D>i<U+0107>|author2=Du<U+0161>ko Topalovi<U+0107>|pages=311-324|volume=14|issue=2|month=December|year=2009|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> Following [[Accession of Croatia to the European Union|accession of Croatia to the EU]], the Adriatic is expected to become an internal sea of the EU.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Nacional (weekly)]]|url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/40630/zerp-je-nepotrebna-avantura|language=Croatian|title=ZERP je nepotrebna avantura|trans_title=ZERP is a needless adventure|author=Robert Bajru<U+0161>i|date=6 December 2007|accessdate=2 February 2012}}</ref>

===Disputes===
Unlike land borders of former Yugoslav republics and subsequently the successor states, their maritime borders were not defined. In addition, the maritime boundary between Albania and Montenegro was not defined before the 1990s. Croatia and Slovenia started negotiations in 1992 but failed to agree resulting in [[Croatia<U+2013>Slovenia border disputes|a dispute]] which was referred to arbitration in 2009. Croatia also declared [[Ecological and Fisheries Protection Zone]] (ZERP) extending to the continental shelf boundary, but its application to the [[Member state of the European Union|EU member states]] was suspended pending definition of the borders. In 2005, Slovenia also declared its protected ecological and continental shelf zone encompassing parts of the Croatia's ZERP. Still the dispute causes no major practical problems in reality. Maritime boundary between Bosnia and Herzegovina and Croatia was formally settled in 1999, but few issues remained in dispute&mdash;[[Klek, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Klek peninsula]] and two islets in the border area. Croatia&ndash;Montenegro maritime boundary is disputed in the Bay of Kotor, at the [[Prevlaka]] peninsula, exacerbated by occupation of the peninsula by the [[Yugoslav People's Army]] and later by [[Military of Serbia and Montenegro|FR Yugoslav Army]], ultimately replaced by an [[United Nations Mission of Observers in Prevlaka|United Nations observer mission]]. The observers left in 2002 and Croatia took over the area as an agreement allowing Montenegrin presence in Croatian waters in the bay was made. The dispute proved far less contentious since independence of Montenegro.<ref name="Geoadria-Borders"/>

==Economy==
===Fishing===
The Adriatic Sea [[Fishery|fisheries]] production varies among countries in the basin. In 2000, nominal total landings of all Adriatic fisheries reached 110&nbsp;thoushand tonnes.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=FAO AdriaMed|url=http://www.faoadriamed.org/pdf/publications/td13/mmm-td-13.pdf|format=PDF|title=Adriatic Sea Fisheries: outline of some main facts|authors=Piero Mannini, Fabio Massa, Nicoletta Milone|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> The largest volume of the fisheries production is achieved in Italy, where the total production volume in 2003 stood at 472&nbsp;thousand tonnes for human consumption and 15&nbsp;thousand tonnes for other purposes. 28.8% of that volume are landings in the Northern and central Adriatic, and 24.5% in Apulia&mdash;Southern Adriatic and Ionian Sea. Italian fisheries, including those operating in outside the Adriatic, employ 60,700 in the [[Primary sector of the economy|primary sector]], including [[aquaculture]] which comprises 40% of the total fisheries production. Gross value of the total fisheries output in 2002 was 1.9&nbsp;billion [[United States dollar|US$]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Food and Agriculture Organization]]|url=http://www.fao.org/fishery/countrysector/FI-CP_IT/en|title=Fishery and Aquaculture Country Profiles - Italy|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref>

In 2006, total Croatian fisheries production volume was 37.8&nbsp;thousand tonnes of catch and 14.2&nbsp;thousand tonnes in marine aquaculture. Croatian fisheries, employ approximately 20,000. Marine capture catch in 2006 in Croatian waters consisted of [[sardine]]s (44.8%), [[anchovy|anchovies]] (31.3%), [[tuna]]s (2.7%), other [[pelagic fish]] (4.8%), [[hake]] (2.4%), [[Mullet (fish)|mullet]] (2.1%), other [[demersal fish]] (8.3%), [[crustacean]]s (largely [[lobster]] and [[Nephrops norvegicus]]) (0.8%), [[shellfish]] (largely [[oyster]]s and [[mussel]]s) (0.3%), [[cuttlefish]] (0.6%), [[squid]]s (0.2%) and [[octopus]]es and other [[cephalopod]]s (1.6%). Croatian marine aquaculture production consists of tuna (47.2%), oysters and mussels (28.2% combined) and [[Bass (fish)|bass]] and [[bream]] (24.6% combined).<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Food and Agriculture Organization]]|url=ftp://ftp.fao.org/FI/DOCUMENT/fcp/en/FI_CP_HR.pdf|format=PDF|title=Fishery Country Profiles - Croatia|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref>

In 2006, Albanian fisheries production amounted to 7,699&nbsp;tonnes, including 1,970&nbsp;tonnes of aquaculture production. At the same time, Slovenian fisheries produced a total of 2,500&nbsp;tonnes with 55% of the production volume originating in aquaculture, representing the highest ratio in the Adriatic. Finally, Montenegrin fisheries production stood at 911&nbsp;tonnes in 2006, with all but 11&nbsp;tonnes coming from capture production.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=FAO AdriaMed|url=http://www.faoadriamed.org/html/country_p/AllCProfile.html|title=Country Fishery Information|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref>

===Tourism===
[[File:Dubrovnik view 01.JPG|thumb|right|[[Dubrovnik]] is a major tourist destination in Croatia]]
[[File:Rimini Waterfront.jpg|thumb|right|[[Rimini]] is a major seaside tourist resort in Italy]]
[[File:Portoroz-hotel Palace.JPG|thumb|right|[[Portoro<U+017E>]] is the largest seaside tourist centre in Slovenia]]
Countries bordering the Adriatic Sea are significant tourist destinations. The largest number of tourist overnight stays and the most numerous tourist accommodation facilities are recorded in Italy, especially in [[Veneto]] region. Veneto is followed by [[Emilia-Romagna]] region and by [[NUTS of Croatia|Adriatic Croatia]] [[Counties of Croatia|counties]]. The Croatian tourist facilities are further augmented by 21&nbsp;thousand nautical ports and [[Mooring (watercraft)|moorings]], as [[nautical tourism|nautical tourists]] are attracted to various types of [[Protected areas of Croatia|protected areas]].<ref name="EU-Casestudy"/> All countries along the Adriatic Sea coasts, except Albania and Bosnia and Herzegovina take part in the [[Blue Flag beach]] certification programme of the [[Foundation for Environmental Education]] for beaches and marinas meeting strict quality standards including environmental protection, water quality, safety and services criteria.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Foundation for Environmental Education]]|url=http://www.fee-international.org/en|title=FEE is...|publisher=Fee-international.org|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> As of January 2012, the Blue Flag is awarded to 103 Italian Adriatic beaches and 29 marinas, 116 Croatian beaches and 19 marinas, 7 Slovenian beaches and 2 marinas, and 16 Montenegrin beaches.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Foundation for Environmental Education]]|url=http://www.blueflag.org/Menu/Awarded+sites|title=Blue Flag Beaches and Marinas|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> 

Tourism is also a significant source of income for those countries, especially so in Croatia and Montenegro where the tourist income generated along the Adriatic coast represents the bulk of tourism income.<ref name="MNE-Stat">{{cite web|publisher=Statistical office of Montenegro|url=http://www.monstat.org/eng/page.php?id=43&pageid=43|title=Tourism|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|publisher=Institute for Tourism (Croatia)|url=http://www.mint.hr/UserDocsImages/Izvj-04_SRTRH.pdf|format=PDF|language=Croatian|authors=Sini<U+0161>a Horak, PhD et al.|title=Glavni plan i strategija razvoja turizma Republike Hrvatske|trans_title=General plan and strategy of development of tourism in the Republic of Croatia|month=November|year=2011|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> Direct contribution of travel and tourism to Croatian GDP stands at 5.1% in 2011, with total contribution of the industry estimated at 12.8% of the national GDP,<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[World Travel and Tourism Council]]|url=http://www.wttc.org/research/economic-impact-research/country-reports/c/croatia/|title=Croatia - Key Facts at a Glance|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> and in case of Montenegro, the direct contribution of tourism to national GDP is 8.1%, with the total contribution to economy at 17.2% of Montenegrin GDP.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[World Travel and Tourism Council]]|url=http://www.wttc.org/research/economic-impact-research/country-reports/m/montenegro/|title=Montenegro - Key Facts at a Glance|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> Tourism in Adriatic Croatia is exhibiting greater growth recently, compared to the other regions around the Adriatic Sea.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=The Rimini Centre for Economic Analysis|url=http://www.rcfea.org/papers/WS1/Quintiliani.pdf|title=International tourism in the coastal regions of five Mediterranean countries|format=PDF|author=Fabio Quintiliani|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref>

