===Oil and gas===
[[Natural gas]] is produced through several projects, including a joint venture started by [[Eni]] and [[INA (company)|INA]] companies which operates two platforms&mdash;one of them is in Croatian waters and draws gas from six wells, and the other one, which started operating in 2010, is located in Italian waters. The Adriatic gas fields were discovered in the 1970s, but their development commenced in 1996. In 2008, INA produced 14.58&nbsp;million [[Barrel of oil equivalent|BOE]] per day of gas.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[INA (company)]]|url=http://www.ina.hr/UserDocsImages/Ina_casopis/zima09-10/44-45%20annamaria.pdf|format=PDF|title=Annamaria offshore oil rig starts trial run|accessdate=30 January 2012|year=2009}}</ref> Approximately a hundred offshore platforms are located in Emilia-Romagna region.<ref name="EU-Casestudy">{{cite web|publisher=[[European Union]]|url=http://ec.europa.eu/maritimeaffairs/documentation/studies/documents/case_study_adriatic_sea_en.pdf|format=PDF|title=The potential of Maritime Spatial Planning in the Mediterranean Sea - Case study report: The Adriatic Sea|date=5 January 2011|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> Eni estimated its [[Concession (contract)|concessions]] in the Adriatic Sea to hold at least {{convert|40000000000|m3|abbr=off}} of natural gas, adding that they may even reach {{convert|100000000000|m3|abbr=off}}. INA estimates, on the other hand, are 50% lower than those supplied by Eni.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=limun.hr|title=Natural gas reserves in the Adriatic may be up to 100 billion cubic meters|url=http://www.limun.hr/en/main.aspx?id=312553|accessdate=30 January 2012|date=22 July 2008}}</ref> Oil was discovered in the Northern Adriatic, at a depth of approximately {{convert|5400|m|abbr=off}}. The discovery was assessed as not viable because of its location, depth and quality.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Rudarsko-geolo<U+0161>ki-naftni zbornik|publisher=[[University of Zagreb]]|issn=0353-4529|title=Istra<U+017E>ivanje i proizvodnja ugljikovodika u Hrvatskoj|url=http://hrcak.srce.hr/13551|trans_title=Prospecting and production of hydrocarbons in Croatia|language=Croatian|volume=8|issue=1|month=December|year=1996|pages=19-25|author1=Josip Se<U+010D>en|author2=<U+017D>arko Prni<U+0107>|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> Those gas and oil reserves are a part of the [[Po basin]] Province of Northern Italy and the Northern Mediterranean Sea.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|url=http://pubs.usgs.gov/of/1999/ofr-99-0050/OF99-50M/occurrence.html|title=Petroleum Systems of the Po Basin Province of Northern Italy and the Northern Adriatic Sea|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref>

In 2000s, investigation works aimed at discovering gas and oil reserves in Middle Adriatic and Southern Adriatic basins was intensified, and by the end of the decade, oil and natural gas reserves were discovered Southeast of Bari and [[Brindisi]]&mdash;Rovesti and Giove oil discoveries. Surveys indicate reserves of 3 billion [[Barrel (unit)|barrels]] of [[oil in place]] and 2 trillion cubic feet of gas in place.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Northern Petroleum|url=http://www.northpet.com/assets/uploads/Proactiveinvestors%20UK%20-%20Northern%20Petroleum%20to%20expand%20exploration%20of%20Rovesti%20and%20Giove%20oil%20discoveries.pdf|format=PDF|date=28 July 2011|accessdate=30 January 2012|title=Northern Petroleum to expand exploration of Rovesti and Giove oil discoveries}}</ref> The discovery was followed by start of further surveys off Croatian coast.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Nafta|volume=60|issue=2|pages=68-82|year=2009|title=New Commercial Oil Discovery at Rovesti Structure in South Adriatic and its Importance for Croatian Part of Adriatic Basin|author1=Sanjin Grandi<U+0107>|author2=Slobodan Kolbah|url=http://hrcak.srce.hr/46152|publisher=[[Croatian Academy of Sciences and Arts]], Scientific commussion for oil|issn=0027-755X|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> In January 2012, INA commenced prospecting for oil off Dubrovnik, marking resumption of oil exploration along the Eastern Adriatic coast after surveys commenced in late 1980s around the island of Bra<U+010D> were cancelled because of the war. Montenegro is also expected to look for oil off its coast.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Slobodna Dalmacija]]|language=Croatian|url=http://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/Hrvatska/tabid/66/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/160871/Default.aspx|title=Naftu i plin vadit <U+0107>emo kod Dubrovnika|trans_title=Oil and gas will be pumped near Dubrovnik|date=11 January 2012|author=Jasmina Mrvaljevi<U+0107>|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> As of January 2012, only 200&nbsp;[[exploration well]]s were sunk off Croatian coast, with all but 30 executed in the Northern Adriatic basin.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Business.hr]]|url=http://www.business.hr/dogadjaji/milanovic-ponistio-kosoricin-natjecaj-za-istrazivanje-nafte-i-plina-106895|title=Milanovi<U+0107> poni<U+0161>tio Kosori<U+010D>in natje<U+010D>aj za istra<U+017E>ivanje nafte i plina|trans_title=Milanovi<U+0107> cancels Kosor's oil and gas exploration tender procedure|language=Croatian|author=Miho Dobra<U+0161>in|date=3 January 2012|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref>

